            <pb n="1" facs="EHRI-BF-19380805_01.jpg"/>
            <!-- <p>When ordering please quote<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2759794/amsterdam.html"
          >Amsterdam</placeName>, Z. V 38 / 57 Jan van Eijck Straat 14</p> -->

            <!--<p><date when="1938-08-05">August 5, 1938</date></p>-->
            <p>Dear Sir –</p>
            <p>The revolting fate of 68 <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2781194/burgenland.html">BURGENLAND</placeName>
                <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term>, driven from their home, received into
                no neighbouring country, nor allowed to return, has been commented upon troughout the international Press.</p>
            <p>Now we receive the report, which we enclose, of distress still encompassing the persecuted, our authority being <persName
                    ref="#ehri_bf_schmolka_marie">Mrs. M. SCHMOLKA</persName>, director of the <orgName
                    ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-395">Hicem</orgName>
                <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>.</p>
            <p>You are free to make such use of the report as you think fit. <persName ref="#ehri_bf_schmolka_marie">Mrs. SCHMOLKA</persName>,
                however, does not wish her name to be mentioned, nor, as usual, must we be named as your source.</p>
            <p rend="margin noindent">Yours faithfully,</p>
            <p rend="margin"><orgName ref="#ehri_bf_jewish_central_information_office">JEWISH CENTRAL INFORMATION OFFICE</orgName></p>
            <p rend="margin"><orgName ref="#ehri_bf_public_service_institute">Public Service Institute</orgName></p>
            <p/>
            <pb n="2" facs="EHRI-BF-19380805_02.jpg"/>
            <p rend="center">THE <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2781194/burgenland.html">BURGENLAND</placeName>
                <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">JEWS</term> on the <hi rend="u">DANUBE TUG –
                    BOAT</hi>
            </p>
            <p rend="center">
                <hi rend="u">An Eye Witness Report</hi>
            </p>
            <p>On <date when="1938-04-16">April 16, 1938</date>, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject"
                    >Jewish inhabitants</term> of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2774348/kittsee.html">Kittsee</placeName> and <placeName
                    ref="http://www.geonames.org/2769259/pama.html">Pama, Burgenland, Austria</placeName>, were ejected from their homes, robbed of
                what money and identity papers they had and, during the night, marooned on some small island in the <placeName
                    ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czech</placeName> section of the <placeName
                    ref="http://www.geonames.org/791630/danube-river.html">Danube</placeName>. On <date when="1938-04-17">April 17</date>, they were
                found by the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czech</placeName> frontier guard and taken to
                    <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3060972/bratislava.html">Bratislava</placeName>. That very same day they were expelled
                from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czecho-Slovakia</placeName> and once again taken to the
                    <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">German</placeName> border. On a narrow streak,
                “No-man’s-land”, somewhere between the borders of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html"
                    >Czecho-Slovakia</placeName>, <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html">Hungaria</placeName> and <placeName
                    ref="http://www.geonames.org/2782113/republic-of-austria.html">Austria</placeName>, they spent three days and nights, in the
                bitter cold, half starved, and without a roof over their heads, between the fixed bayonets of the sentries of all 3 countries which
                they were not allowed to enter. Some of them, 17 in all, managed to get back to <placeName
                    ref="http://www.geonames.org/2774348/kittsee.html">Kittsee</placeName>, where the old men and children were locked up in a cellar,
                and the grown ups, men and women, were made do hard <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-555" type="subject"
                    >scrubbing work</term>. Exhausted from 3 days’ starving, the poor people’s strength threatened to fail, but ruthless beating put
                them to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> again. During the night, after a
                30 miles walk, they were taken back to the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8505031/czechoslovakia.html">Czech</placeName>
                frontier.</p>
            <p>At long last the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> of <placeName
                    ref="http://www.geonames.org/3060972/bratislava.html">Bratislava</placeName> found a temporary way-out. They hired a tug-boat,
                which landed on the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html">Hungarian</placeName> side of the <placeName
                    ref="http://www.geonames.org/791630/danube-river.html">Danube</placeName>, near <placeName
                    ref="http://www.geonames.org/3045991/rajka.html">Royka</placeName>, and received the people, 68 altogether, agricultural workers
                and merchants, infants and 80 years old men. No country along the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/791630/danube-river.html"
                    >Danube</placeName> being prepared to grant the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-101" type="subject"
                    >refugees</term> leave on land, the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html">Hungarian</placeName> authorities
                extend the permit from week to week, hoping that the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-868" type="subject"
                    >Jewish organisations</term> will secure their <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject"
                    >emigration</term> overseas. It is now three months that these people, smitten with despair, refused by every country, and even
                grudged the stay aboard the ship – it is now three months that they are thus kept in the vague hope of salvation.</p>
            <p><pb n="3" facs="EHRI-BF-19380805_03.jpg"/>Efforts were made to induce various countries overseas to receive these unfortunates. Though
                some of the inmates of the boat managed to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject"
                    >emigrate</term> to the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/6252001/united-states.html">United States</placeName>, the
                majority could not be <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject">emigrated</term>, being unable
                to comply with the requirements set up by the countries overseas. It was in full realisation of this plight of theirs that we went to
                see the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-101" type="subject">refugees</term> on the boat, on July 10.</p>
            <p>We have seen their unspeakable mental distress, even increased by physical torture, as they either must stay in the narrow rooms
                downstairs which are infested with rats and vermin, or on the upper deck where they are left to the weather’s mood.</p>
            <p>There must be an end to this awful tragedy. It is not enough that <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864"
                    type="subject">Jewry</term> must suffer all the humiliation that is being heaped upon it? Are we going to proclaim no, before the
                whole world, our utter helplessness, deliver up these poorest of the poor to the <orgName
                    ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName>, and allow a mass <term
                    ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-217" type="subject">suicide</term>? We have taken down all particulars of
                every one of these unfortunates, and in addition, worked out a plan to lead this problem towards its solution, it being in the last
                resort nothing more than a question of finance: 4.000 Pounds.</p>
